text: Analytical and Bioanalytical Chemistry https://doi.org/10.1007/s00216-018-1315-0 Characterization and mapping of secondary metabolites of Streptomyces sp. from caatinga by desorption electrospray ionization mass spectrometry (DESI–MS) Júlia Pereira Rodrigues 1 & Shamina Saiyara Prova 2 & Luiz Alberto Beraldo Moraes 1 & Demian Rocha Ifa 2 Received: 12 June 2018 / Revised: 17 July 2018 / Accepted: 7 August 2018 # Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2018

Abstract The discovery of new secondary metabolites is a challenge to biotechnologists due to the emergence of superbugs and drug resistance. Knowledge about biodiversity and the discovery of new microorganisms have become major objectives; thus, new habitats like extreme ecosystems have become places of interest to research. In this context, caatinga is an unexplored biome. The ecosystem caatinga is a rich habitat for thermophilic microbes. Its high temperature and dry climate cause selective microbes to flourish and become established. Actinobacteria (Caat 1- 54 genus Streptomyces sp.) isolated from the soil of caatinga was investigated to characterize and map its secondary metabolites by desorption electrospray ionization mass spectrometry imaging (DESI–MSI). With this technique, the production of bioactive metabolites was detected and associated with the different morphological differentiation stages within a typical Streptomyces sp. life cycle. High-resolution mass spectrometry, tandem mass spectrometry, UV–Vis profiling and NMR analysis were also performed to characterize the metabolite ions detected by DESI–MS. lienomycin, along with the A novel compound, which is presumed to be an analogue of the antifungal agent antimicrobial compound lysolipin I were identified in this study to be produced by the bacterium. The potency of these bioactive compounds was further studied by disc diffusion assays and their minimum inhibitory concentrations (MIC) against Bacillus and Penicillium were determined. These bioactive metabolites could be useful to the phar- maceutical industry as candidate compounds, especially given growing concern about increasing resistance to avail- able drugs with the emergence of superbugs. Consequently, the unexplored habitat caatinga affords new possibilities for novel bioactive compound discovery. Keywords Ambient ionization . Desorption electrospray ionization (DESI) . Secondary metabolites . NMR . UV–Vis . Antibiotics Júlia Pereira Rodrigues and Shamina Saiyara Prova contributed equally to this work. 1 Department of Chemistry, Faculdade de Filosofia Ciências e Letras de Ribeirão Preto, University of São Paulo, Av. Bandeirantes 3900, Ribeirão Preto, São Paulo 14040-901, Brazil 2 Centre for Research in Mass Spectrometry, Department of Chemistry, York University, Chemistry Building, 4700 Keele Street, Toronto, ON M3J IP3, Canada The understanding of biodiversity and the discovery of new microorganisms have become an inevitable part of the field of biotechnology, owing to their potential in generating a rich and assorted library of new bioactive compounds. With the emer- gence of superbugs and the increasing resistance to available drugs in the pharmaceutical field, exploration of new sources of bioactive metabolites became essential [1, 2]. New habitats such as marine, mountains and deserts are thus places of inter- est to many biotechnologists [3]. Accordingly, caatinga, which is only prevalent in Brazil, appears to be a biome with unex- plored biological potential and will hence prove to be an im- portant source for new active compounds [4, 5]. Caatinga is in the tropical zone and has a hot semi-arid climate. Since the biome is located in a semi-arid region, the soil has lower amounts of organic matter, with 50% being sedimentary and rich in groundwater [6]. The average precip- itation is about 250 to 1000 mm causing scarcity of water almost throughout the year [7]. Consequently, the habitants of this ecosystem have high resilience power because of their ability to adapt to extreme conditions [8]. The diversity of species is lower in relation to other biomes; however, there lies a high bioprospecting potential. Likewise the conditions are favourable for actinomycetes, which mainly establish themselves in different kinds of soils [9].

Actinomycetes are high GC (guanine-cytosine) content, Gram-positive bacteria with fungal morphology. Similarly to fungi actinomycetes grow to form vegetative mycelium and produce spores [9]. Although they have different characteris- tics in different biological backgrounds, their common fea- tures are assumed to be due to their adaptation in similar ecological niches [10]. Briefly, when the spore acquires suit- able conditions and nutrients, it germinates and grows into one or two germ tubes to become hyphaes. The vegetative hyphae grow perpendicularly to form extensions and branches also known as vegetative mycelia, which are evident over the sur- rounding substrate. As a result of nutrient depletion and/or other factors, morphological differentiation causes the aerial hyphae to break open in the air. The aerial hyphae fragments then start to divide to form chains of pre-spore compartments that later mature into spores [11] (see Electronic Supplementary Material, Fig. S1). The spores typically can survive in a dor- mant state for a long time. Actinomycetes are a rich source of secondary metabolites with diverse biological activities. Overall, they contribute to about 70% of the available antibi- otics and various other non-antibiotic bioactive metabolites such as enzymes, enzyme inhibitors, immunological regulators and antioxidants which are of numerous practical use and high commercial value. Among actinomycetes, the largest group studied is Streptomyces spp., accounting for up to 95% of the actinomycetes found in soil [12, 13]. The actinobacteria were isolated from the rhizosphere of caatinga which is defined as the part of soil that is in direct contact with roots of the plants. It is a niche with great microbial diversity and likewise aids acti- nomycetes to reside and offer advantages to plants through the production of various bioactive compounds [14, 15].

Currently, identification and investigation of any active metabolite from a microbe involves its isolation by performing conventional chromatographic techniques with a spectrometric mode of detection e.g. HPLC, GC, UV–Vis, NMR and MS. All of these techniques require multiple sets of analysis to be performed prior to their detection and iden- tification, thus making the overall process time consuming and laborious. Matrix assisted laser desorption ionization mass spectrometry (MALDI–MS) offers to solve this prob- lem, since it can be used directly on the colony for instantaneous detection of metabolites. MALDI alone or coupled with secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS) was recently reported to offer imaging in order to understand the distribution of metabolites in bacterial colonies and biofilms [16–18]. However, the use of a matrix to ionize analytes for detection purposes is an unavoidable sample preparation step [19, 20]. Desorption electrospray ionization mass spectrome- try (DESI–MS) and rapid evaporative ionization mass spec- trometry (REIMS) on the other hand are ambient ionization techniques that allow direct analysis of sample surfaces with almost no sample preparation and consequently are gaining popularity in various fields as an easy mode of analysis [21–23]. Few studies involving DESI–MS and REIMS have been reported in the field of microbiology [23, 24]. The requirement of high spray and gas pressures to perform DESI hinders its use directly on the agar plate or on soft, uneven surfaces like fungi. Fungi, unlike bacteria, have soft and irregular morphology due to the formation of spores and hyphae [25–27]. In this work, an actinobacteria colony was mapped for metabolites using DESI–MS imag- ing (DESI–MSI). Since actinobacteria have similar mor- phology to fungi, imprint DESI–MSI was performed for detection and mapping of metabolites [27, 28]. Along with imprint DESI–MSI, direct analysis and imaging of the bac- teria were performed with the use of a glass slide inside agar plate as reported by Angolini et al. [29].

In this paper, DESI–MS and DESI–MSI were used to de- tect, characterize and map secondary metabolites from actinobacteria Caat 1-54 colony (Streptomyces mashuensis, ATCC 2934) isolated from caatinga. Production of these me- tabolites was monitored by performing analysis with cultures of different incubation lengths (4 and 14 days) to better un- derstand the environmental impact on their release. High- resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS), tandem mass spec- trometry, NMR and UV profiling were also performed to com- prehend the structural features of the major metabolites detect- ed by DESI–MS. Inhibition bioassays with fungi, Gram- positive and Gram-negative bacteria were conducted to check the potency of crude growth media of the bacterium. Furthermore, minimum inhibitory concentrations (MIC) of the purified metabolites were also determined. Bacterial and fungal culture conditions Autoclaved ISP-2 medium was used to inoculate with Caat 1- 54 glycerol stock. The culture was grown overnight (16–18 h) at 37 °C and 200 rpm. The next day a single spore was col- lected from the flask using a 1000-μL pipette tip and was placed on top of a previously made potato dextrose agar (PDA) plate having a glass slide underneath. The PDA plate Characterization and mapping of secondary metabolites of Streptomyces sp. from caatinga by desorption... with the bacteria was incubated at 37 °C for 4 to 14 days. After the required incubation time, the plates were stored at 4 °C until further use to conduct DESI–MS and DESI–MSI exper- iments to map secondary metabolites. For performing disc diffusion assay, crude bacterial growth medium was used. The crude growth medium extract was obtained upon incubating Caat 1-54 in ISP-2 medium at 37 °C and 200 rpm for 4 and 14 days. After the required incubation time, the medium was centrifuged to get rid of the bacterial residues followed by impregnating them on discs made from filter papers.

Penicillium sp. (P. roqueforti) was selectively grown from blue cheese. Briefly, using a pipette tip, the blue fungi was scrapped off from the cheese and was used to inoculate previ- ously autoclaved distilled water. The resulting solution was incubated at 28 °C without shaking for 48 h. After 2 days (48 h), 600 μL of the solution was spread on a previously made PDA plate using a glass rod and the plate was later incubated at 28 °C for another 2 days. For both E. coli and B. subtilis 168, the respective bacterial glycerol stock was used to inoculate autoclaved LB medium. The seed culture was grown for 16–18 h at 37 °C for E. coli and 30 °C for B. subtilis at 200 rpm. The next day, 600 μL of the culture solution was poured on the LB agar plates to per- form the disc diffusion study. The respective plates of E. coli and B. subtilis were incubated at their respective temperatures (30 °C for B. subtilis, 37 °C for E. coli) for another 16 h. DESI–MS and DESI–MSI experiments

After 4 and 14 days of incubation of Caat 1-54 strain on the PDA plate at 37 °C, the solid medium was dried into a thin film. Prior to running DESI–MS and DESI–MSI experiments a glass slide having a single colony was separated from the dried plate [29] (ESM, Fig. S2) and was fixed on a custom built 2D moving stage by the use of adhesive tape; or a double-sided tape imprint from the colony was made and ad- hered on a glass slide. Typical instrument parameters such as capillary voltage and temperature were set at 5 kVand 285 °C, respectively. The mobile phase used was a mixture of metha- nol, water and formic acid in the ratio 9:0.9:0.1. The flow rate of the solvent was maintained at 5 μL/min with simultaneous nebulization by N2 gas set at 100 psi. The sprayer was kept at an incident angle of 52–54°, 1–2 mm above the slide surface and 2–4 mm away from the inlet of the mass spectrometer to maintain an overall collection angle of 10–12° into the inlet of the mass spectrometer. All the analysis was performed in pos- itive ion mode, scanning the mass range of m/z 500–1400. The MS injection time was set to 200 ms and three scans were averaged to obtain a spectrum. Data acquisition and manage- ment was performed using X-calibur 2.0 software from Thermo Fischer Scientific (San Jose, USA).

For DESI imaging, the sprayer was rastered over the sample surface in a horizontal direction at a constant speed of 179 μm/s until 90 to 130 vertical rows were scanned to obtain a full image. DESI–MSI spatial resolu- tion was achieved by setting the coordinate or pixel size to 150 μm. Prideaux et al. reported that the resolution of DESI–MSI is restricted to the inner diameter of the cap- illary carrying the charged solvent and the distance it is placed away from the surface under analysis [30]. In this study, the inner capillary used to carry the charged solvent had a diameter of 50 μm, so a pixel size set to 150 μm ensured a greater area for solvent contact and thereby higher signal intensity and also a minimal region of overlap between spots. No further reference was used to assess the resolution accuracy. BioMap imaging soft- ware compatible with the X-calibur spectral data was used to obtain ion images in two-dimensional coordinates.

Caat 1-54 strain was grown in ISP-2 medium for 4 to 14 days at 37 °C and 200 rpm. At the end of either 4 or 14 days the resultant medium was separated from the bacteria by centrifu- gation at 3000 × g for 3 min. Discs were made from filter papers of medium porosity with the use of a paper punch. A 100-μL aliquot of the centrifuged medium was used to soak each disc to be used for conducting the inhibition study. B. subtilis, E. coli and P. roqueforti were evenly spread using a glass rod onto their respective agar plates from overnight seed culture. Upon spreading, the culture solution was allowed to dry for some time (3–5 min) inside the biosafety cabinet. Tweezers were used to place the soaked disc at the centre of the plate and pushed a little deeper for enhanced diffusion of the medium components into agar. Later the plate was incubated at 28 °C for P. roqueforti for 48 h and 16 h for B. subtilis and E. coli at 30 and 37 °C, respectively. A ruler was used to measure the diameter of the zone of inhibition. An imprint of the inhibition zone was also taken on a PTFE (hard density polytetrafluoroethylene sheet) surface for further anal- ysis of the distribution of chemical determinants from the impregnated disc on the agar surface by DESI–MS. Note that PTFE surfaces are porous and impermeable, which allowed enhanced signal intensity and stability to image the distribu- tion of chemicals appropriately [27]. As negative control, discs were soaked in autoclaved ISP-2 medium prior to introduction into the respective culture plates of B. subtilis, E. coli and P. roqueforti and were incubated for the same duration of time as the test plates. Refer to ESM for protocols regarding high-resolution and tandem mass spectrometry, isolation and purification of active compounds and minimum inhibitory concentra- tion determination.

The intensity of the most abundant ion is 7E01. b DESI– MS scan of a colony after 14 days of incubation at 37 °C on potato agar plate. The intensity of the most abundant is 2E02 DESI analysis and imaging Upon DESI analysis of the bacteria directly from the glass slide after 4 days and 14 days of incubation, peaks corre- sponding to ions of m/z 1229, 626, 634, 606 and 598 were observed (Fig. 1). To check if there were other detectable secondary metabolites produced by the bacteria, an im- print of the top surface of the colony was made on double-sided tape. DESI analysis of the imprint showed a relatively high abundance of the metabolite at m/z 598 after both 4 days and 14 days of incubation (ESM, Fig. S3). Interestingly m/z 605, 626, 634 and 1229 were absent on the spectrum obtained from the imprint. Hard Fig. 2 DESI–MS imaging (DESI–MSI) of a colony directly from glass slide after a 4 days or b 14 days of incubation at 37 °C on potato agar plate

imprinting (hard press on the tape and for long duration) on the double-sided tape showed the presence of both m/z 598 and 1229 but at a relatively low signal intensity com- pared to direct analysis from aglass slide or soft imprint on tape. These observations led to the conclusion that the cream-coloured cells were the new dividing cells near to the medium surface. As further cells divide, the old ones are pushed to the top. As a result of nutrition depletion the top layer dries up and the bacteria under stress (aged cells) produce the compound at m/z 598 and, upon press- ing it hard to get an imprint, the aged cells cover the top of the tape along with some young cells from underneath, where the ion of m/z 1229 becomes apparent. Since the dry aged bacterial cell residue resided at the top of the tape imprint, the signal to noise ratio of both the ions, m/z Characterization and mapping of secondary metabolites of Streptomyces sp. from caatinga by desorption... Fig. 3 DESI–MS imaging (DESI–MSI) of an imprint of a colony on double-sided tape after a 4 days or b 14 days of incubation at 37 °C on potato agar plate 598 and 1229, appeared low (ESM, Fig. S3c). All the scans were performed multiple times (more than three times) and the profile obtained was reproducible.

Our hypothesis was further supported by the results ob- tained by DESI imaging. Spatio-temporal distribution of the compounds was checked by performing DESI–MSI. It was observed that the compound at m/z 1229 was only apparent at both the centre and edges after 4 days of incubation (Fig. 2) but only at the edges after 14 days of incubation. In the optical images (Fig. 2a, b) the presence of m/z 1229 was only evident at the cream-coloured region of the bacteria. This supports the notion that the secondary metabolite at m/z 1229 was synthesized by the healthy young cells of the bac- terial colony. If these young cells (cream coloured) were cov- ered by old cells (white coloured) the signal for m/z 1229 declines, which is the reason why when the ion of m/z 1229 was mapped in the ion images the compound did not appear as a full solid circle. In contrast, the ion of m/z 598 appears at the top surface of the dried bacterial residue. Imprinting from the top surface using tape helps to trap the dried surface on the sticky tape film and thus can be imaged adequately by DESI–MSI (Fig. 3). Whereas, the high gas pressure blows away most of the dried material while rastering through the colony surface for data acquisition during imaging directly from the glass slide. Furthermore, spectra from the imprints showed the ion Fig. 4 Structure of compounds identified: a lysolipin I and b lienomycin of m/z 583 which is a characteristic peak from the tape (ESM, Fig. S3). This ion can be considered to understand the produc- tion pattern of the compound at m/z 598. Several scan analyses of tape imprints for both 4 and 14 days led to the conclusion that after 4 days of incubation the compound m/z 598 is rela- tively less produced compared to the amount produced after 14 days of incubation (Figs. S3a, S3b (see ESM), 4a and 4b) with respect to the tape ion peak at m/z 583.

On the basis of conventional analytical techniques associ- ated with searches of databases such as the Dictionary of Natural Products and high-resolution mass spectrometry and tandem mass spectrometry (described in detail later in the paper), the ion of m/z 1229 was identified as an analogue of lienomycin (having an additional hydroxylation followed by double bonding in the parent lienomycin moiety) and the ion of m/z 598 as lysolipin I. Therefore, we hypothesize that the production of the lienomycin analogue occurs during the for- mation of germ tube and vegetative mycelium. On the other hand, lysolipin I is associated with the sporulation stage [11]. DESI–MS not only helps to identify and localize the metabo- lites but also to understand their role in the bacterial life cycle under different environmental conditions. In conclusion, all these observations suggest that the bacteria under stress con- ditions produce the compound of m/z 598, whereas healthy viable bacterial cells produce mostly the metabolite of m/z 1229. This is also supported by the colony images obtained upon imaging them directly from the glass slide as after 4 days it is seen that the cream-coloured cells (optical image) and the spatio-temporal distribution of the compound at m/z 1229 are relatively higher than that observed in the optical image and chemical ion images of the colony after 14 days of incubation. Along with the compounds at m/z 598, 605, 626, 634 and 1229, the DESI–MS spectrum shows that Caat 1-54 also pro- duces many other secondary metabolites at m/z 669, 707 and others, which have relatively low abundance or ionization efficiency in the current extraction solvent and thus needs other solvents or conventional means of characterization through separation by HPLC prior to their identification. High-resolution and tandem mass spectrometry

The dried potato dextrose agar plates with the bacteria colony were soaked in DESI spray solvent, vortexed and centrifuged to obtain an extract; this was further diluted 500-fold with the same solvent prior to direct infusion into the mass spectrometer to perform high-resolution and tandem mass spectrometry. Initially, the crude extract was analysed by high-resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS) to identify the compounds apparent while performing DESI–MS and DESI– MSI. Remarkable amounts of ions at m/z 598.1114, 605.3605, 625.8626, 633.8497 and 1228.7489 were observed in the HRMS scan. The HRMS spectrum (ESM, Fig. S4) obtained upon direct infusion showed the presence of these ions that enabled their structural identification through tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS). Table 1 summarizes the mass discrepancies calculated between the proposed the- oretical masses and the experimental parent and fragment ions observed. For all ions the difference observed was below 3.5 ppm. Among the tentatively identified ions, one of the secondary metabolites released by actinobacteria Table 1 Discrepancy between the observed and theoretical exact masses as observed with HRMS by an Orbitrap mass spectrometer 605.3615 625.8626 633.8497 598.1114 1210.7254 1192.7154 1174.7042 1156.6936

Caat 1-54 was previously isolated and identified using techniques, such as high- conventional analytical performance liquid chromatography–mass spectrometry (HPLC–MS) and nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) [31], as lysolipin I, and other most abundant, readily ion- ized secondary metabolite detected and identified in this work is a new compound, an analogue of lienomycin, the macrolide polyene pentaene (Fig. 4b) [32]. Other ions at m/z 605, 626 and 634 are doubly charged ions, as ob- served in the profile shown in Fig. S8 (ESM). The ions at m/z 626 and m/z 634 correspond to the adducts [M + H + Na]2+ and [M + H + K]2+, respectively of the ion at m/z 1229, and the ion at m/z 605 corresponds to the dou- ble protonated adduct of the major fragment ion of m/z 1211 formed from the parent ion m/z 1229. A relatively large number of polyenes were recently re- ported as metabolites from actinomycetes [33]. These molecules were characterized by the presence of a hy- droxylated macrocyclic lactone ring, usually attached to a sugar moiety; typically they are recognised on the basis of the characteristic chromophoric property observed ow- ing to the presence of three to seven conjugated double bonds in the macrolactone ring. These structures are com- monly very large, bearing a lactone ring of 26–44 carbons atoms and are named as trienes, tetraenes, pentaenes, hexaenes and heptaenes according to the number of con- jugated double bonds. They also display unique physico- chemical properties, which include strong UV–Vis light absorption and poor water solubility [34]. Polyenes with five conjugated double bonds, commonly known pentaenes, show UV bands around 317, 331 and 349 nm [36]. The absorption profile observed with the compound at m/z 1229 was similar having bands at 318, 333 and 349 nm (ESM, Fig. S6). Thus the presence of three coincident peaks in the absorption profile help to char- acterize the compound at m/z 1229 as like the general pentenes [37] and an analogue of lienomycin. Usually, purification of these compounds requires multiple chromatographic separa- tions, but since concomitant degradation is also evident, often, distribution of d m/z 626, e m/z 1229, f m/z 669, g m/z 605, h m/z 598 in the region imaged. i Ion image showing the distribution of m/z 699 in the region imaged from fungus. rather than improving the purity level, impurities from degra- dation build up in the purified material. However, in the region of 300 nm there is relatively low interference due to degrada- tion products in the UV profile. The fragmentation profile and ultraviolet absorption character- istics are consistent with the molecule belonging to the same class as lienomycin (Fig. 1b). Supporting information was sought using NMR spectroscopy. Although the purity of the sample was less than optimal, there were several resonances consistent with a lienomycin-like structure. NMR analysis con- firmed the presence of an ester moiety, a ketone, vinylic carbons and protons, hydroxylated carbon and a primary amine in the structure of the compound; this supported the characterization as an analogue of leinomycin. Please refer to ESM for a more detailed explanation based on NMR analysis.

A disc diffusion study was performed to further verify the production of the antibacterial and antifungal agent iden- tified as lysolipin and lienomycin analogue, respectively, by mass spectrometry. Figure S14 (ESM) shows that the crude extract is active against fungus (P. roqueforti) and Gram-positive bacteria (B. subtilis) but inactive against Gram-negative bacteria (E. coli). The medium from 14 days of Caat 1-54 incubation produced a larger zone of inhibition than the medium extracted after 4 days of incubation of Caat 1-54 and this can be easily attributed to the increased accumulation of the active metabolites in the culture medium after the prolonged incubation period. Higher concentrations of lysolipin and lienomycin ana- logue in the culture medium resulted in increased activity against bacteria and fungus. Again, the crude medium proved to have a more potent antifungal effect than anti- bacterial effect as shown by the size of the diameter of the zone of inhibition (ESM, Fig. S14): an average inhibition zone diameter of 4 mm was measured from the P. roqueforti plate having discs with medium obtained after 14 days of incubation of Caat 1-54; whereas in the case of B. subtilis, the zone was measured to be around 2 mm in diameter from the same medium extract.

The zone of inhibition was imaged by DESI–MS using the moving stage to map the distribution of active components (Fig. 5). It was found that compounds from the growth medi- um uniformly diffused into the zone of inhibition and at the point where the microbe (fungus or bacteria) starts re- establishing their intensity was the least. All these observa- tions reinforce that the compounds with m/z 598 and 1229 are actually responsible for inhibition of growth of the bacteria and fungus, forming the clear zone of inhibition. Their radial diffusion from the disc onto the agar plate restricted the growth of the microbe around the disc, at the zone of inhibi- tion (clear region), and once the concentration reduces below the minimum inhibitory concentration, the microbe starts re- establishing. Figure 5i maps ions at m/z 699 from fungal sur- face, whereas Fig. 5j and k map two ions at m/z 745 and 793 from the agar plate to show that they have uniform intensity throughout the region mapped. The region where the disc was placed appeared dark when mapped for the compounds from the growth medium (Fig. 5d–h). This led to the assumption that after the required incubation time the disc went dry and so imprinting from it did not result in a sufficient amount of compounds getting transferred on the PTFE surface. Again the radial diffusion from the disc itself reduced its actual con- centration and thus appeared to be devoid of those compounds at that specific region. Minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC)

The compounds identified in this study were purified in order to better comprehend their individual functions and potency. Figure S15 (ESM) shows lysolipin I’s activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B. subtilis and fungus P. roqueforti, whereas the analogue of lienomycin shows only antifungal activity against P. roqueforti. This preliminary observation led us to perform MIC bioassays against the microorganisms to understand the potency of each compound against the tar- gets. The MIC for lysolipin I was around 0.8 μg/mL against B. subtilis 168 and 1.6 μg/mL against P. roqueforti, while the analogue of lienomycin had a MIC around 0.4 μg/mL against P. roqueforti (ESM Fig. S16). This confirms that the antifun- gal activity with the crude extract (ESM Fig. S14) was a cu- mulative effect of both compounds, lysolipin I and lienomycin analogue; whereas the anti-Gram-positive activity was only due to the presence of lysolipin I.

On the basis of the morphological differentiation of Streptomyces, compounds identified in this work can be correlated with the life cycle of the bacterium. We hypoth- esize that the analogue of lienomycin is produced during the initial step of the formation of germ tube and vegeta- tive mycelium. On the contrary, lysolipin I may be a prod- uct during the sporulation stage. It is evident from this study that Caat 1-54 is an excellent source of useful sec- ondary metabolites. The fact that the crude growth media does not require any sample preparation like isolation and/or concentration of the active compound to exhibit their activity demonstrates the efficacy of the compounds as an antifungal and anti-Gram-positive agent. Direct and imprint DESI–MSI analyses show different distribution profiles of the metabolites which reinforces the need for three-dimensional mapping of the bacterial colony that would enable detection and characterization of all the me- tabolites released by the bacterium at different stages of its lifespan. Ambient techniques such as DESI–MS and DESI–MSI proved to a very useful to monitor, character- ize and map metabolites directly from the bacteria. In conclusion, caatinga is a rich habitat that needs more attention to explore the prevalent wide range of thermophilic to microbes. The region will be of high interest Characterization and mapping of secondary metabolites of Streptomyces sp. from caatinga by desorption... biotechnologists as it will serve as a potential source of new lead compounds that are yet to be discovered.
